First, we know that $\binom{26}{13}$ is equal to $\frac{26!}{13!13!}$. Next, we know $\binom{27}{14}$ is equal to $\frac{27!}{14!13!}$. Using a <solution> </solution> identity, we get $\frac{26!}{13!13!}+\frac{26!}{n!(26-n)!}=\frac{27!}{14!13!}$. Dividing both sides by $\frac{26!}{13!13!}$, we obtain $1+\frac{13!13!n!(26-n)!}{26!14!13!}=\frac{27}{14}$. Using a <solution> </solution> identity, we get $1+\frac{n!(26-n)!}{26!13!14}=\frac{27}{14}$. Subtracting 1 from both sides, we obtain $\frac{n!(26-n)!}{26!13!14}=\frac{13}{14}$. Cross multiplying gives us $\frac{14n!(26-n)!}{26!13!}=13$. Simplifying the left hand side gives us $\frac{(26-n)!}{(26-n)!(13-n)!}=13. \newline$ There is only one way to distribute 13 - n objects to (26 - n) objects, which is if $n=\text{ }$\boxed{1}.</solution> <solution>oggleมุulers={42]});
